    "engine": "knitr",
    "markdown": "# Pharmacodynamics and Dose-Response\n\n## Learning Objectives\n\nBy the end of this chapter you will be able to:\n\n- Distinguish direct and indirect pharmacodynamic effects\n- Differentiate graded and quantal responses\n- Fit Emax, sigmoid Emax, linear, and log-linear PD models in R\n- Interpret $E_{max}$, $EC_{50}$, and Hill coefficient\n- Understand baseline effect, maximal response, and variability\n\n---\n\n## What Is Pharmacodynamics?\n\nPharmacodynamics describes the relationship between drug concentration (or dose) and the magnitude of the pharmacological effect. The fundamental question is:\n\n> *Given a certain drug concentration at the site of action, how large is the effect?*\n\n---\n\n## The Emax Model\n\n### Model Equation\n\n$$E = E_0 + \\frac{E_{max} \\cdot C}{EC_{50} + C}$$\n\nwhere:\n- $E$: Observed effect\n- $E_0$: Baseline effect (at $C = 0$)\n- $E_{max}$: Maximum drug-attributable effect\n- $EC_{50}$: Concentration producing 50% of $E_{max}$\n- $C$: Drug concentration\n\n\n::: {.cell}\n\n```{.r .cell-code}\nlibrary(ggplot2)\nlibrary(dplyr)\n\n# Visualize the Emax model\nconc <- 10^seq(-2, 3, length.out = 200)\nEmax <- -80   # e.g., 80% reduction (negative Emax for inhibition)\nE0   <- 100   # baseline = 100%\nEC50 <- 10\n\neffect <- E0 + (Emax * conc) / (EC50 + conc)\n\ndf_emax <- data.frame(conc, effect)\n\nggplot(df_emax, aes(conc, effect)) +\n  geom_line(color = \"#C44536\", linewidth = 1.2) +\n  geom_vline(xintercept = EC50, linetype = \"dashed\", color = \"gray50\") +\n  geom_hline(yintercept = E0 + Emax, linetype = \"dashed\", color = \"gray50\") +\n  annotate(\"text\", x = EC50 * 2, y = E0 + 0.5 * Emax,\n           label = paste0(\"EC50 = \", EC50), hjust = 0) +\n  scale_x_log10() +\n  labs(title = \"Emax Model\",\n       subtitle = paste0(\"E0 = \", E0, \", Emax = \", Emax, \", EC50 = \", EC50),\n       x = \"Concentration (log scale)\", y = \"Effect\") +\n  theme_minimal()\n```\n\n::: {.cell-output-display}\n![](09-pd-dose-response_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-1-1.png){width=2400}\n:::\n:::\n\n\n---\n\n## The Sigmoid Emax Model\n\n### Model Equation\n\n$$E = E_0 + \\frac{E_{max} \\cdot C^{\\gamma}}{EC_{50}^{\\gamma} + C^{\\gamma}}$$\n\nThe Hill coefficient ($\\gamma$) controls the steepness of the curve:\n- $\\gamma = 1$: Standard Emax\n- $\\gamma > 1$: Steeper (more switch-like)\n- $\\gamma < 1$: Shallower (more gradual)\n\n\n::: {.cell}\n\n```{.r .cell-code}\n# Compare different Hill coefficients\nconc <- 10^seq(-2, 3, length.out = 200)\nE0 <- 0\nEmax <- 100\nEC50 <- 10\ngamma_values <- c(0.5, 1, 2, 5)\n\ndf_sigmoid <- expand.grid(conc = conc, gamma = gamma_values) %>%\n  mutate(\n    effect = E0 + (Emax * conc^gamma) / (EC50^gamma + conc^gamma),\n    gamma = factor(paste0(\"γ = \", gamma))\n  )\n\nggplot(df_sigmoid, aes(conc, effect, color = gamma)) +\n  geom_line(linewidth = 1) +\n  scale_x_log10() +\n  labs(title = \"Sigmoid Emax Model: Effect of Hill Coefficient\",\n       x = \"Concentration (log scale)\", y = \"Effect (% of maximum)\",\n       color = \"Hill Coefficient\") +\n  scale_color_manual(values = c(\"#D4A843\", \"#C44536\", \"#0B6E6B\", \"#1B365D\")) +\n  theme_minimal()\n```\n\n::: {.cell-output-display}\n![](09-pd-dose-response_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-2-1.png){width=2400}\n:::\n:::\n\n\n### Interpreting the Hill Coefficient\n\n| $\\gamma$ | Curve Shape | Biological Interpretation |\n|----------|-------------|--------------------------|\n| < 1 | Shallow, gradual | Multiple binding sites with negative cooperativity |\n| = 1 | Standard hyperbola | Simple 1:1 binding |\n| > 1 | Steep, switch-like | Positive cooperativity, signal amplification |\n| >> 1 | Nearly step function | Ultrasensitive systems |\n\n---\n\n## Linear and Log-Linear Models\n\n### Linear Model\n\n$$E = E_0 + S \\cdot C$$\n\nUsed when the therapeutic range is well below $EC_{50}$.\n\n### Log-Linear Model\n\n$$E = m \\cdot \\ln(C) + b$$\n\nCommon in the 20–80% effect range on a log scale.\n\n\n::: {.cell}\n\n```{.r .cell-code}\n# Compare Emax, linear, and log-linear in therapeutic range\nconc_range <- seq(1, 50, length.out = 100)\nEC50 <- 30\nEmax <- 80\n\n# Emax\neff_emax <- (Emax * conc_range) / (EC50 + conc_range)\n# Linear approximation (slope at C=0 is Emax/EC50)\neff_lin <- (Emax / EC50) * conc_range\n# Log-linear (fitted in mid-range)\neff_loglin <- 20 + 30 * log10(conc_range)\n\ndf_models <- data.frame(\n  conc = rep(conc_range, 3),\n  effect = c(eff_emax, eff_lin, eff_loglin),\n  Model = rep(c(\"Emax\", \"Linear\", \"Log-Linear\"), each = length(conc_range))\n)\n\nggplot(df_models, aes(conc, effect, color = Model)) +\n  geom_line(linewidth = 1) +\n  labs(title = \"PD Model Comparison\",\n       x = \"Concentration\", y = \"Effect\") +\n  scale_color_manual(values = c(\"#C44536\", \"#0B6E6B\", \"#D4A843\")) +\n  theme_minimal()\n```\n\n::: {.cell-output-display}\n![](09-pd-dose-response_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-3-1.png){width=2400}\n:::\n:::\n\n\n---\n\n## Fitting PD Models in R\n\n\n::: {.cell}\n\n```{.r .cell-code}\n# Simulate dose-response data\nset.seed(123)\ndoses <- c(0.1, 0.3, 1, 3, 10, 30, 100, 300)\nn_rep <- 4\n\npd_data <- expand.grid(DOSE = doses, REP = 1:n_rep) %>%\n  mutate(\n    Emax = 90, EC50 = 10, E0 = 5,\n    Effect_true = E0 + (Emax * DOSE) / (EC50 + DOSE),\n    Effect_obs  = Effect_true + rnorm(n(), 0, 3)\n  )\n\n# Fit Emax model\nfit_emax <- nls(Effect_obs ~ E0 + (Emax * DOSE) / (EC50 + DOSE),\n                data = pd_data,\n                start = list(E0 = 0, Emax = 80, EC50 = 5))\nsummary(fit_emax)\n```\n\n::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}\n\n```\n\nFormula: Effect_obs ~ E0 + (Emax * DOSE)/(EC50 + DOSE)\n\nParameters:\n     Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    \nE0     4.0984     0.9741   4.207 0.000227 ***\nEmax  90.4666     1.3961  64.801  < 2e-16 ***\nEC50   9.4163     0.6610  14.245 1.26e-14 ***\n---\nSignif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1\n\nResidual standard error: 2.909 on 29 degrees of freedom\n\nNumber of iterations to convergence: 4 \nAchieved convergence tolerance: 3.15e-06\n```\n\n\n:::\n:::\n\n\n\n::: {.cell}\n\n```{.r .cell-code}\n# Fit sigmoid Emax model\nfit_sig <- nls(Effect_obs ~ E0 + (Emax * DOSE^gamma) / (EC50^gamma + DOSE^gamma),\n               data = pd_data,\n               start = list(E0 = 0, Emax = 80, EC50 = 10, gamma = 1))\nsummary(fit_sig)\n```\n\n::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}\n\n```\n\nFormula: Effect_obs ~ E0 + (Emax * DOSE^gamma)/(EC50^gamma + DOSE^gamma)\n\nParameters:\n      Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    \nE0     3.51986    1.39117    2.53   0.0173 *  \nEmax  91.84270    2.82221   32.54  < 2e-16 ***\nEC50   9.46661    0.71386   13.26 1.36e-13 ***\ngamma  0.95835    0.06916   13.86 4.65e-14 ***\n---\nSignif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1\n\nResidual standard error: 2.943 on 28 degrees of freedom\n\nNumber of iterations to convergence: 4 \nAchieved convergence tolerance: 6.935e-06\n```\n\n\n:::\n:::\n\n\n\n::: {.cell}\n\n```{.r .cell-code}\n# Plot fits\ndose_pred <- 10^seq(-2, 3, length.out = 200)\npred_emax <- predict(fit_emax, newdata = data.frame(DOSE = dose_pred))\npred_sig  <- predict(fit_sig, newdata = data.frame(DOSE = dose_pred))\n\ndf_pred <- bind_rows(\n  data.frame(DOSE = dose_pred, Effect = pred_emax, Model = \"Emax\"),\n  data.frame(DOSE = dose_pred, Effect = pred_sig,  Model = \"Sigmoid Emax\")\n)\n\nggplot(pd_data, aes(DOSE, Effect_obs)) +\n  geom_point(size = 2, alpha = 0.6, color = \"gray40\") +\n  geom_line(data = df_pred, aes(DOSE, Effect, color = Model), linewidth = 1.2) +\n  scale_x_log10() +\n  labs(title = \"Fitted PD Models\",\n       x = \"Dose (log scale)\", y = \"Effect\") +\n  scale_color_manual(values = c(\"#0B6E6B\", \"#C44536\")) +\n  theme_minimal()\n```\n\n::: {.cell-output-display}\n![](09-pd-dose-response_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-6-1.png){width=2400}\n:::\n:::\n\n\n---\n\n## Graded vs Quantal Responses\n\n| Response Type | Description | Example | Analysis |\n|---------------|-------------|---------|----------|\n| **Graded** | Continuous effect magnitude | Blood pressure reduction (mmHg) | Emax, linear models |\n| **Quantal** | Binary (yes/no) outcome | Death/survival, response/no response | Logistic regression, $ED_{50}$ |\n\n\n::: {.cell}\n\n```{.r .cell-code}\n# Quantal dose-response: logistic regression\nset.seed(456)\ndoses_q <- rep(c(1, 3, 10, 30, 100), each = 20)\n# Probability of response = Emax model with variability\nlogit_p <- -2 + 1.5 * log10(doses_q)\np <- plogis(logit_p)\nresponse <- rbinom(length(doses_q), 1, p)\n\nquantal_data <- data.frame(DOSE = doses_q, Response = response) %>%\n  group_by(DOSE) %>%\n  summarise(N = n(), Responders = sum(Response), .groups = \"drop\") %>%\n  mutate(Fraction = Responders / N)\n\n# Fit logistic regression\nfit_logit <- glm(cbind(Responders, N - Responders) ~ log10(DOSE),\n                 family = binomial, data = quantal_data)\n\n# Predict for smooth curve\ndose_pred <- 10^seq(0, 2.5, length.out = 100)\npred_p <- predict(fit_logit, newdata = data.frame(DOSE = dose_pred),\n                  type = \"response\")\n\nggplot(quantal_data, aes(DOSE, Fraction)) +\n  geom_point(size = 3, color = \"#C44536\") +\n  geom_line(data = data.frame(DOSE = dose_pred, Fraction = pred_p),\n            color = \"#0B6E6B\", linewidth = 1.2) +\n  scale_x_log10() +\n  labs(title = \"Quantal Dose-Response\",\n       x = \"Dose (log scale)\", y = \"Fraction Responding\") +\n  theme_minimal()\n```\n\n::: {.cell-output-display}\n![](09-pd-dose-response_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-7-1.png){width=2400}\n:::\n:::\n\n\n---\n\n## Receptor Theory: The Mechanistic Basis of PD Curves\n\nThe empirical Emax and sigmoid Emax models describe concentration-effect data well, but they don't explain *why* the curves have that shape. Receptor theory bridges this gap by deriving PD curves from the fundamental chemistry of drug-receptor binding.\n\n### Mass-Action Binding\n\nThe simplest model: a drug molecule ($L$) binds reversibly to a receptor ($R$):\n\n$$R + L \\underset{k_{-1}}{\\stackrel{k_1}{\\rightleftharpoons}} RL$$\n\nAt equilibrium, the dissociation constant $K_d$ is:\n\n$$K_d = \\frac{k_{-1}}{k_1} = \\frac{[R][L]}{[RL]}$$\n\nThe fraction of receptors occupied (**occupancy**, $\\theta$) follows the Langmuir isotherm:\n\n$$\\theta = \\frac{[RL]}{[R]_{total}} = \\frac{[L]}{K_d + [L]}$$\n\nThis is exactly the **same functional form as the Emax model** — the Emax curve arises naturally from simple 1:1 binding. $EC_{50}$ corresponds to $K_d$, and $E_{max}$ corresponds to the maximal response when all receptors are occupied.\n\n\n::: {.cell}\n\n```{.r .cell-code}\n# Demonstrate receptor occupancy as a function of concentration\nL <- 10^seq(-2, 3, length.out = 200)\nKd <- 3.5\n\n# Occupancy (Langmuir isotherm) vs Emax model\noccupancy <- L / (Kd + L)\nemax_equiv <- L / (Kd + L) * 100  # scaled to 100%\n\ndf_receptor <- data.frame(\n  Concentration = rep(L, 2),\n  Value = c(occupancy, emax_equiv / 100),\n  Curve = rep(c(\"Occupancy (θ)\", \"Emax (scaled)\"), each = length(L))\n)\n\nggplot(df_receptor, aes(Concentration, Value, color = Curve)) +\n  geom_line(linewidth = 1.2) +\n  scale_x_log10() +\n  geom_vline(xintercept = Kd, linetype = \"dashed\", alpha = 0.5) +\n  annotate(\"text\", x = Kd * 1.5, y = 0.5, label = paste0(\"Kd = \", Kd), hjust = 0) +\n  labs(title = \"Receptor Occupancy = Emax Model\",\n       subtitle = \"The Emax curve is the Langmuir binding isotherm\",\n       x = \"[L] (log scale)\", y = \"Fraction\", color = \"\") +\n  scale_color_manual(values = c(\"#0B6E6B\", \"#C44536\")) +\n  theme_minimal()\n```\n\n::: {.cell-output-display}\n![](09-pd-dose-response_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-8-1.png){width=2400}\n:::\n:::\n\n\n### From Occupancy to Effect: The Operational Model of Agonism\n\nNot all occupied receptors produce the same effect. The **operational model of agonism** (Black & Leff, 1983) accounts for the transduction efficiency between binding and response:\n\n$$E = \\frac{E_{max} \\cdot \\theta^n}{\\theta^n + K_A^n}$$\n\nSubstituting $\\theta = [L]/(K_d + [L])$ gives a function that reduces to the sigmoid Emax model under most conditions. This explains why the Hill coefficient ($\\gamma$) can differ from 1 even with simple 1:1 binding — it reflects **signal amplification** downstream of the receptor.\n\n::: {.theory-box}\n### The Chain: Binding → Occupancy → Effect\n\n$$\\text{Mass action: } R+L \\rightleftharpoons RL \\quad\\rightarrow\\quad \\theta = \\frac{[L]}{K_d+[L]}$$\n\n$$\\text{Operational model: } E = E_{max} \\cdot \\frac{\\theta^n}{\\theta^n + K_A^n}$$\n\n$$\\text{Empirical (Hill): } E = E_{max} \\cdot \\frac{[L]^\\gamma}{EC_{50}^\\gamma + [L]^\\gamma}$$\n\nThese three equations form a nested hierarchy — each is a special case or generalization of the one above.\n:::\n\n---\n\n## Agonism, Antagonism, and Allosteric Modulation\n\n### Agonists\n\nAn **agonist** binds to a receptor and produces a response. The potency is reflected in $EC_{50}$ (or $K_d$), and the efficacy in $E_{max}$.\n\n### Competitive Antagonism\n\nA **competitive antagonist** binds to the same site as the agonist but produces no response. It shifts the dose-response curve to the right without reducing $E_{max}$:\n\n$$E = E_{max} \\cdot \\frac{[A]}{[A] + EC_{50} \\cdot (1 + [B]/K_B)}$$\n\nwhere $[A]$ is agonist concentration, $[B]$ is antagonist concentration, and $K_B$ is the antagonist's dissociation constant.\n\n\n::: {.cell}\n\n```{.r .cell-code}\n# Competitive antagonism: rightward shift without Emax reduction\nA <- 10^seq(-2, 3, length.out = 200)\nEC50 <- 8; Emax <- 100\nB_conc <- c(0, 2, 8, 25)  # antagonist concentrations\nKB <- 4                      # antagonist Kd\n\ndf_antag <- expand.grid(A = A, B = B_conc) %>%\n  mutate(\n    EC50_app = EC50 * (1 + B / KB),\n    Effect = Emax * A / (EC50_app + A),\n    Antagonist = factor(paste0(\"[B] = \", B))\n  )\n\nggplot(df_antag, aes(A, Effect, color = Antagonist)) +\n  geom_line(linewidth = 1) +\n  scale_x_log10() +\n  labs(title = \"Competitive Antagonism\",\n       subtitle = \"Rightward shift in dose-response curve; Emax preserved\",\n       x = \"[Agonist] (log scale)\", y = \"Effect (% of maximum)\") +\n  scale_color_manual(values = c(\"#0B6E6B\", \"#D4A843\", \"#C44536\", \"#1B365D\")) +\n  theme_minimal()\n```\n\n::: {.cell-output-display}\n![](09-pd-dose-response_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-9-1.png){width=2400}\n:::\n:::\n\n\n### Non-Competitive Antagonism\n\nA **non-competitive antagonist** binds to an allosteric site and reduces the maximal response without shifting $EC_{50}$ (in the pure case), or both reduces $E_{max}$ and shifts $EC_{50}$:\n\n$$E = \\frac{E_{max}}{1 + [B]/K_B} \\cdot \\frac{[A]}{[A] + EC_{50}}$$\n\n### Allosteric Modulation\n\n**Allosteric modulators** bind at a site distinct from the orthosteric (agonist) site and change receptor affinity ($\\alpha$) and/or efficacy ($\\beta$):\n\n- **Positive allosteric modulator (PAM)**: increases agonist affinity or efficacy\n- **Negative allosteric modulator (NAM)**: decreases agonist affinity or efficacy\n\n::: {.key-box}\n### Clinical Significance\n\nUnderstanding antagonism mechanisms is essential for:\n- **Reversal agents**: Naloxone (competitive antagonist) reverses opioid overdose\n- **DDI prediction**: Co-administered antagonists shift the effective dose\n- **Therapeutic window**: Irreversible antagonists can cause prolonged effects\n:::\n\n---\n\n## Variability in PD\n\nSources of variability in PD:\n\n- **Inter-individual**: Different patients, different responses\n- **Intra-individual**: Same patient, different occasions\n- **Measurement error**: Assay variability\n- **Tolerance/desensitization**: Response changes over time\n\n\n::: {.cell}\n\n```{.r .cell-code}\n# Visualize inter-individual variability in PD\nset.seed(789)\nn_subjects <- 20\nconc <- 10^seq(-1, 3, length.out = 100)\n\n# Each subject has a different EC50\npd_pop <- expand.grid(conc = conc, ID = 1:n_subjects) %>%\n  mutate(\n    EC50_ind = rlnorm(n(), log(10), 0.5),  # log-normal variability in EC50\n    Emax_ind = rnorm(n(), 80, 10),          # normal variability in Emax\n    Effect   = (Emax_ind * conc) / (EC50_ind + conc)\n  )\n\nggplot(pd_pop, aes(conc, Effect, group = ID)) +\n  geom_line(alpha = 0.3, color = \"#0B6E6B\") +\n  scale_x_log10() +\n  labs(title = \"Inter-Individual Variability in PD\",\n       subtitle = \"Each line = one subject; EC50 varies log-normally\",\n       x = \"Concentration (log scale)\", y = \"Effect\") +\n  theme_minimal()\n```\n\n::: {.cell-output-display}\n![](09-pd-dose-response_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-10-1.png){width=2400}\n:::\n:::\n\n\n---\n\n::: {.exercise-box}\n### Exercises\n\n1. Fit an Emax model to simulated data. Report $E_{max}$, $EC_{50}$, and their standard errors.\n2. How does the Hill coefficient change the shape of the sigmoid Emax curve? Plot for $\\gamma$ = 0.5, 1, 2, 4.\n3. Generate quantal dose-response data and estimate $ED_{50}$ using logistic regression.\n4. A drug has $E_{max}$ = -60 (inhibition), $EC_{50}$ = 5 ng/mL, and $\\gamma$ = 1. What concentration is needed for 80% of maximum effect?\n5. Compare the AIC of Emax, sigmoid Emax, and linear models for a given dataset. Which is preferred?\n:::\n\n::: {.mistakes-box}\n### Common Mistakes\n\n- **Using linear models when the drug approaches $E_{max}$** — linear extrapolation overestimates effect\n- **Ignoring baseline ($E_0$)**: Always measure and model the baseline\n- **Confusing $EC_{50}$ with potency**: Lower $EC_{50}$ means more potent\n- **Forcing $\\gamma = 1$ without checking**: Test whether the sigmoid model improves fit\n- **Extrapolating far beyond the observed concentration range**\n:::\n\n::: {.key-box}\n### Key Takeaway\n\nThe Emax and sigmoid Emax models are the workhorses of PD analysis. Understand the meaning of $E_{max}$, $EC_{50}$, and $\\gamma$. Always plot your data before fitting, consider baseline effects, and be aware that PD variability can be substantial between individuals.\n:::\n",
